******
[2] Nuble
Date: Wed 12 Jan 2022
Source: Biobio Chile [in Spanish, trans., edited]
https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-de-nuble/2022/01/12/hombre-de-29-anos-es-la-primera-victima-fatal-por-virus-hanta-en-la-region-de-nuble-este-2022.shtml


This Wednesday [12 Jan 2022] the health authority confirmed the 1st death from a hantavirus infection in the Nuble region this 2022. The individual is a 29 year old man who would have acquired the virus in the Andes area of the region after carrying out sport fishing activities. The deceased, who lived in Chillan, died last Friday [7 Jan 2022] at the Herminda Martin Clinical Hospital.

The SEREMI [Secretaria Regional Ministerial de Salud; regional health ministerial secretariat], Marcela Cuadra, reported that the environmental epidemiological investigation established the Los Lleuques sector, in the Pinto community, as a possible place of infection. There, the man took part in sport fishing, where he entered an area with bushes during the first 2 weeks of December [2021].

The patient presented symptoms in the last few days of the year [2021], being hospitalized in the intensive care facility until his death due to hantavirus pulmonary syndrome, a diagnosis confirmed by the Institute of Public Health (ISP). His case is the 3rd reported in 2021. The other 2 were a woman aged 24 and a girl of 12.

Given the situation, the SEREMI reinforced educational work in the rural sector, for people who work in the fields and for tourists. In Pinto, hygiene kits were delivered to cabin owners to avoid new cases of infection.

[byline: Daniela Salgado]

--
communicated by:
ProMED

[The above reports are of 2 cases of a hantavirus infection in different regions of Chile. Although not specified in these or previous reports from the regions, the hantavirus involved in these cases no doubt is Andes virus. This virus is endemic in Chile, and cases of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome occur there every year. Andes virus can be transmitted directly person to person but only with very close physical proximity, usually within the family. However, unless specific laboratory tests are done, Seoul hantavirus cannot be ruled out.

Images of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligoryzomys_longicaudatus#/media/File:Raton_colilarga.jpg. - Mod.TY

ProMED map of Chile: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8700987,7.]
